topic:
The exercise options shown are NOT the “best” exercises - they are just motions that are loaded in a clear way to demonstrate the principles of 1) how to move to potentially load the abs and then 2) how to pick a load direction and application that makes sense for each motion. There are tons of great options that do not involve cables but that involve DBs, machines, Jerry-rigged machines, and bodyweight. Principles > specific prescriptions.
Another aside: I did not include “TVA” exercises because the TVA is involved in all of these to some degree to hold your spine and gut together. The TVA can’t be targeted specifically, but likely plays a big role in any bracing exercise, like squats, deadlifts etc.

topic: There are confounding variables when trying to identify why/how elite-level sprinters have highly developed glutes. Genetics play a massive role, and there’s a clear selection bias in professional sports for people who already have certain body parts naturally developed more than others. In some sense though, this still proves the point - those who naturally have strong butts often end up as high-level sprinters, and I don’t think this is a coincidence at all. Don’t take my word for it - mimic the mechanics in a stable setting and see for yourself!
